node.text: I’m late posting this, but better late than never. When a photo editor asks you to take their engagement photos, there is almost no higher compliment. That’s even more true when they’ve been your dear friend for over a decade. Congratulations to @tannercurtis and @yo_powe, thank you for trusting me to make these portraits of you to celebrate your upcoming nuptials. NGL I was a little disappointed that TK didn’t join us but she’s always been a bit of a diva so whatever. 😺

node.text: I recently photographed @tscandii, a former sex worker and the founder of Black Trans Nation, a mutual aid nonprofit she founded last year (@black_trans_nation) for a @nytimes story on two competing bills designed to protect sex workers: one that features full decriminalization, one that centers on what used to be referred to a the “Nordic” or “Swedish” model and is focused on punishing pimps and sex buyers. I chose to photograph her on medium format film as well as with a digital camera, as I find it really interesting to compare the two. Curious what you guys think about the differences between film and digital? Which do you prefer? Thanks as always to @jfurt for the assignment!

node.text: There’s a type of light that happens in NYC that I never see out in natural/rustic settings, or really almost anywhere else for that matter. It’s what happens when light reflects off of a skyscraper and back onto the street. It’s spooky and beautiful and I could photograph people walking through it all day. It’s just one of the tiny idiosyncrasies I love about living here.

node.text: Sometimes you work on a story and meet someone that just makes you feel like a big old slacker. They’re just that impressive. Dr. Alexandra Friedman is one of those people. She just graduated from medical school and obtaining a residency in pediatrics. Dr. Friedman’s graduation makes her one of the few female Hasidic doctors in the country. She’s also a mother to 10 (!) children, including 3 under 3. She was gracious enough to allow me to make a portrait of her and her lovely children, who I had face away from the camera to grant them privacy at her request. I had them stand on the footprint of their family sukkah (a special canopy constructed from foliage during the weeklong fall holiday of Sukkot.) Dr. Friedman is going to do amazing things for her community, I am sure of it. Link to her story in @nytimes is in my bio. Thank you a million times to @andrewhinderaker for putting me on this!

node.text: Happy Birthday to my best friend @floridaangie. To say you’re one of the most beautiful people I know feels sort of trite, but it’s true. You are funny, passionate, spunky, resilient, wise, kind and resourceful, and watching you be a mother to your two daughters (my other two favorite people) fills me with awe. You are also ridiculously attractive and have a top notch 🍑. I truly feel so damn lucky to be your friend. I love you Ang!

node.text: A tiny juniper branch I made from a pattern by @harvestgoodsco. Juniper is good at growing in thin or depleted soils, or soils that are polluted.  This makes it a critical tree for replanting and regeneration of the land. I think we are all probably feeling our soil is a bit “depleted” right now. Do what you gotta do to regenerate (preferably without depleting someone else’s soil!) #embroidery #bordadopictórico

node.text: Nafiah Ikram is a 21-year-old Hofstra student. On March 17th, an unknown attacker threw a cup of battery acid in her face. The acid fused her contact lens to one eye, partially blinding her. The family has no answers so far, but believe Nafiah was targeted. This is far-and-away one of the most disturbing stories I’ve ever worked on. But Nafiah was an incredibly bright, lovely and kind young woman, and we worked together to make a portrait that she felt would tell her story with dignity and strength. I know she’ll go far in life. A GoFundMe has been started to help with Nafiah’s medical bills, which I am linking in my bio. Thank you forever to @jfurt for trusting me with this devastating story. Link to story in the comments.

node.text: Finally back making images after 3 months and it feels so good to be working again. This is from a profile I shot in Manhattan DA candidate Tali Weinstein. Weinstein is of Persian Jewish descent and we talked about her growing up Sephardic in a mostly Ashkenazi community, and she also gave a me a few tips on how to successfully make tahdig. Thanks @andrewhinderaker for the assignment!

node.text: As many of you know, I broke my ankle two days before Christmas in a bike accident. The surgeon’s exact words were, “it looked like a bomb went off in your cartilage.” I had no idea how totally disorienting it could be to be immobilized, and had no idea how deeply I took for granted my ability to move my body the way I want. I suddenly couldn’t do any of the things I’d been doing during the panda bear to keep myself sane. I ended up randomly decided I was going to learn embroidery after spending many years favoriting patterns on Etsy. I took a course with @gimenaromero on @domestika and let me tell you, as a creative person and as someone who constantly needs projects to focus energy on, this endeavor saved my sanity. It’s been really hard not being able to pick up a camera and make work that way, but it’s been great to do something totally new and different and it’s re-sparked my creativity. I can’t wait to go out and make photos again, and I also am gonna share some non-photo creative endeavors on here from time-to-time from now on. I know I’m late to the game but since this is my first post of the year, happy 2021! #embroidery #needlepainting #domestika #robin #bird #thread #dmcthreads
